(10, 1, '2013-04-10 17:10:03', '2013-04-10 17:10:03', '<p class="bodytxt"><strong>Amorphous â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>Without a clear shape as in a wound dressing in gel form</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Antimicrobial â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>An agent that inhibits the growth of bacteria</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Arterial Ulcer</strong>Â â€“ Related to the presence of arterial occlusive disease.Â  Presenting symptoms mainly involve pain and tissue loss.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Autolytic Debridement</strong>Â - Removal of devitalized tissue through normal wound exudateÂ or through the use of anyÂ topical dressing or preparation that encourages moisture retention or by the bodyâ€™s own mechanisms</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Bedsore</strong>Â â€“ The traditional name for a pressure ulcer. Also called a decubitus ulcer.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Beefy Red</strong>Â â€“ A term used to describe a healthy looking wound with good blood supply</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Blanching</strong>Â â€“ To become white with pressure</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Biocompatible</strong>Â â€“ refers to the ability of a product to perform its desired function without eliciting any undesirable effects</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Cellulitis</strong>Â â€“ Inflammation of tissue characterized by redness.Â  Signifies a spreading infection.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Chemical Debridement</strong>Â â€“ The removal of dead or devitalized tissue by using enzymatic debriding agents.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Chronic Wound</strong>Â â€“ A wound that takes longer than normal to heal due to underlying conditions such as pressure, diabetes, poor circulation, immune deficiencies or infection.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Contraction</strong>Â â€“ The pulling together of wound edges/margins in the healing process.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>CWOCN</strong>Â â€“ Same as â€œET Nurseâ€ (Certified wound, ostomy, continence nurse).</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>CWS</strong>Â â€“ Certified Wound Specialist</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Debride</strong>Â â€“ to remove dead or devitalized tissue</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Debridement</strong>Â â€“ Removal of dead or devitalized tissue.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Decubitus Ulcer</strong>Â â€“ The Latin term for a pressure ulcer. (Sometimes referred to as a â€œdecub.â€)</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Dehisced</strong>Â â€“ Describes a surgical wound which has broken open or is not healing properly</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Denuded</strong>Â â€“ Loss of epidermis.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Depth</strong>Â â€“ Distance from the woundâ€™s surface downward. The last measurement in wound description in centimeters.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Dermis</strong>Â â€“ The second layer of skin that contains hair follicles, sweat glands, sebaceous glands, blood vessels and lymph vessels: involved in stage 2, 3, and 4 pressure ulcers as well as partial and full thickness wounds.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Edema</strong>Â â€“ Observable swelling from fluid accumulation in body tissues</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Enterostomal Therapy Nurse or Certified Wound, Ostomy, Continence Nurse</strong>Â â€“Â <br /> Often referred to as â€œET nurse.â€Â  Nurse who provides Care expertise to patients with abdominal stomas, draining Â wounds and fistulas, incontinence and general wound care.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Epidermis</strong>Â â€“ The outer cellular layer of the skin</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Epiboly</strong>Â â€“ edges of the top layer of the epidermis roll down to cover lower edge of epidermis, causing the inability of epithelial cells to migrate from wound edges. Wound healing cannot take place in this circumstance.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Epithelialization â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>Regeneration of the epidermis across a wound surface</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Erythema</strong>Â â€“ Redness of the skin surface produced by widening of the blood vessels.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Eschar</strong>Â â€“ Thick, leathery dead or devitalized tissue.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Etiology</strong>Â â€“ The science and study of the causes of diseases and their mode of operation.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>ET nurse</strong>Â â€“ Commonly used term for an Enterostomal Therapy Nurse.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Excoriation</strong>Â â€“ Linear scratches on the skin.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Exudate</strong>Â â€“ Accumulation of fluids in a wound.Â </p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Fenestrated â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>sliced or cut open</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Fibrous Tissue</strong>Â â€“ Tightly bound yellow film found on the granulation tissue surface composed of or containing fibroblasts</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Friable</strong>Â â€“ refers to a delicate wound that may bleed easily</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Friction</strong>Â â€“ Surface damage caused by skin rubbing against another surface.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Full Thickness Wound</strong>Â â€“ Tissue destruction extending through the dermis to involve subcutaneous tissue and possibly muscle/bone.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Granulation Tissue</strong>Â â€“ The formation or growth of small blood vessels and connective tissue in a full thickness wound and a stage 3 and 4 pressure ulcer: beefy red, shiny, granular tissue which generally indicates healing.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Growth Factors -</strong><strong>Â </strong>refers to naturally occurring substances capable of stimulating cellular growth and proliferation</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Hydrophilic</strong>Â â€“ Attracting moisture</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Hydroactive â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>Activated by moisture</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Hypertonic â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>movement of water from a high H2O concentration inside the cell, to a low H2O concentration outside the cell. Hypertonic wound dressings pull water or exudateÂ out of an area and create a moist environment that is more conducive to wound healing.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Hypergranulation â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>Increased thickness in the granular layer of the epidermis.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Ionic exchange</strong><strong>Â </strong><strong>â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>Denotes the processes of purification, separation, and decontamination.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Infection</strong>Â â€“ Overgrowth of microorganisms capable of tissue destruction and invasion, accompanied by local or systemic symptomsÂ </p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Inflammation</strong>Â â€“ Defensive reaction to tissue injury: involves increased blood flow and capillary permeability Signs and symptoms include heat, redness, swelling and pain of the affected area.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Inflammatory Phase</strong>Â â€“ The first phase in the normal wound healing process that lasts approximately from time of the initial injury to four days post injury.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Ischemia</strong>Â â€“ A deficiency of blood supply due to functional constriction or obstruction of a blood vessel.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Maceration</strong>Â â€“ A â€œwaterloggedâ€ appearance of the area surrounding a wound which is an indication of excessive moisture or an inappropriate dressing or dressing application.Â Â Â </p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Macrophage</strong>Â â€“ â€œGiant Eater:â€ eats up unwanted dead tissue, cleans the wound and releases chemicals.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Mechanical Debridement</strong>Â â€“ The removal of dead or devitalized tissue, for example by the use of wet-to-dry dressings, whirlpool or surgical debridement.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Moisture Retentive Dressings</strong>Â â€“ Dressings that allow wounds to remain moist.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>MMPâ€™s â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>Enzymes in chronic wounds which when imbalanced with their natural inhibitors can become destructive and delay the healing process.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Necrotic</strong>Â â€“ Dead</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Negative pressure</strong>Â â€“ a vacuum-action that is used to reduce pressure around a wound, drawing out excess fluids and cellular wastes.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Non-occlusive â€“</strong><strong>Â </strong>Allowing the passage of moisture and air</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Occlusive</strong>Â - A dressing that prevent the passage of air that can dry out a wound bed or to prevent unwanted or unneeded moisture from going into or out of an area.Â </p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Osmotic</strong>Â â€“ relating to osmosis: a physical process in which a solvent moves, without input of energy, across a semi-permeable membrane. This term relates to movement of wound fluid from one place to another.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Osteomyelitis</strong>Â â€“ Inflammation of the bone marrow and adjacent bone.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Partial Thickness Wound</strong>Â â€“ Tissue destruction through the epidermis extending into but not through the dermis.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Periwound</strong>Â â€“ Around the wound</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Permeability</strong>Â -Â  Ability to pass through</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Pressure Ulcer</strong>Â â€“ An area of localized damage caused by ischemia due to pressure.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Serous</strong>Â â€“ Producting a serous secretion or containing serum</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Sinus tract</strong>Â â€“ A pathway which can extend in any direction from the wound surface resulting in dead space</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Sodium Hypochlorite</strong>Â â€“ a chemical compound frequently used as a disinfecting agent</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Slough â€“</strong> Necrotic tissue that is usually loose, stringy, yellow, tan, white or gray in color.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Shear</strong>Â â€“ Trauma caused by tissue layers sliding against each other.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Stasis</strong>Â â€“ Stagnation of blood caused by venous congestion.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Staging</strong>Â â€“ An anatomical description of depth used to describe pressure ulcers.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Surgical Debridement</strong>Â â€“ The removal of dead or devitalized tissue by a physician or trained healthcare professional at the bedside or in the operating room.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Tunneling</strong>Â â€“ Tissue destruction underlying intact skin along wound margins.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Ulcer</strong><strong>Â </strong>â€“ An open lesion or sore</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Undermining</strong>Â â€“ Another term used to describe tunneling: tissue destruction underlying intact skin along wound margins</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Vasoconstriction</strong>- Dilation of blood vessels</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Vasodilation</strong>Â â€“ Dilation of blood vessels</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Venous</strong>Â â€“ pertaining to the veins.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>Venous Ulcer</strong>Â â€“ Local losses of epidermis and variable levels of dermis and subcutaneous tissue occuring over or near the ankle and/or lateral lower leg.</p> <p class="bodytxt"><strong>WOCN</strong>Â â€“ An acronym for Wound,Â Ostomy, Continence Nurse<br />Â </p> <p>Â </p>', 'Wound Terminology', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'wound-terminology', '', '', '2013-04-10 17:10:03', '2013-04-10 17:10:03', '', 0, 'http://admedonlinenew.dev:8888/?p=10', 5, 'post', '', 0),
(11, 1, '2013-04-10 17:10:03', '2013-04-10 17:10:03', '<p><strong><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">GAUZE ROLLS &amp; GAUZE SPONGES</a></strong></p> <p><strong>ANTIMICROBIAL GAUZE WRAP â€“ ANTIMICROBIAL GAUZE SPONGE</strong><br /><br />Roll gauze impregnated with anÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#antimicrobial"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">antimicrobial</span></a>Â substance to prevent contamination of a wound site.</p> <p><strong>Examples:Â <br />Bioguard roll gauze<br />Bioguard gauze spongeÂ <br />Kerlix AMDÂ </strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br />Use on any wound site to prevent infection from entering the wound site from the outsideÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Prevents infection by eliminating bacteriaÂ <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications</strong>Â <br />None known</p> <hr /> <p>Â </p> <p><strong><a id="anasept" name="anasept"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/proddetail.asp?prod=antimicrobial%5Fanasept%5Fspray">ANASEPT SPRAY</a></strong><br /><br />Anasept is an extremely safe and gentle antimicrobial skin and wound cleanser with exceptionally rapid broad-spectrum bactericidal, fungicidal and virucidal properties. Â It is a pure, colorless, isotonic, tissue-compatible solution and has a two-year shelf life.</p> <p>Anasept will eliminate bacteria and fungi within 2 minutes or less including resistant strains such as MRSA, VRE, Pseudomonas, Candida albicans and Aspergillus niger. Â There is no known microbial resistance to Anasept.</p> <p>This product may be used as a wound cleanser and to prepare sites for IV fluids, dialysis, central lines and more.</p> <hr /> <p><br /><a name="alginate"></a><strong><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">CALCIUM ALGINATE DRESSINGS</a></strong><br /><strong>Secondary dressing should be used to coverÂ </strong><br /><br /><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#hydrophilic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Hydrophilic</span></a>, non-woven fiber dressings that are derived from seaweed and when contacted by woundÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>Â form a gel mass in the wound.Â  These come in a sheet or rope form and are absorbent.</p> <p><strong>Examples:Â <br />AlgicelÂ <br />MelgisorbÂ <br />ReliamedÂ </strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br /><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#partial_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Partial thickness</span></a>Â andÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#full_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">full thickness</span></a>Â wounds having moderate to heavyÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>, Infected wounds, Filling cavities, tracts and<a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#undermining"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">undermining</span></a>,Â <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#partial_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Partial thickness</span></a>Â andÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#full_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">full thickness</span></a>Â woundsÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Absorbs excessÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>Â while maintaining a moist wound environment FacilitatesÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#autolytic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">autolytic debridement</span></a>Â of loose,Â <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#necrotic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">necrotic</span></a>Â tissueÂ <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications</strong>Â <br />Dry woundsÂ </p> <hr /> <p><br /><a name="alginatesilver"></a><strong><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">CALCIUM ALGINATE WITH SILVER</a></strong><br /><strong>Secondary dressing should be used to coverÂ </strong><br /><br />Same composition and indications as calcium alginate with silver added forÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#antimicrobial"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">antimicrobial</span></a>Â benefits.</p> <p><strong>Examples:<br />Silverlon CAÂ <br />Algicel AG<br />Reliamed AG-CMC (hydrofiber)</strong></p> <p><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br />Draining wounds with signs of infection Filling cavities, tracts andÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#undermining"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">undermining</span></a>Â <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Absorbs excessÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>Â while maintaining a moist wound environment FacilitatesÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#autolytic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">autolytic debridement</span></a>Â of loose,Â <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#necrotic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">necrotic</span></a>Â tissue Decreases or eliminates bacterial load in an infected woundÂ <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications:</strong>Â <br />Do not use with hydrogelsÂ <br />Should not be used with products that create an ionic exchange in the wound siteÂ <br />Cannot be used with enzymes (ie Santyl Collagenase)Â <br /><br /></p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="alginatehoney"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">CALCIUM ALGINATE WITH HONEY</a></strong><br /><strong>Secondary dressing should be used to cover</strong>Â <br /><br />Active Leptospermum Honey impregnated into a calcium alginate pad.Â  As woundÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>Â is absorbed, the alginate forms a gel to assist in maintaining a moist wound environment for optimal wound healing.Â  Alginate is removable in one piece.</p> <p><strong>Example: Â Â Â Â <br />MedihoneyÂ </strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â diabetic foot ulcers, leg ulcers, pressure ulcersÂ <br />1st and 2nd degreeÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#partial_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">partial thickness</span></a>Â burnsÂ <br />donor sitesÂ <br />traumatic and surgical woundsÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â Cleanses and debrides lowers overall wound pH promotes a moisture-balanced environment eliminates bacteria and multi-resistant bacteria with natural honey</p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="collagen"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">COLLAGEN DRESSINGS</a></strong><br /><br />These dressings come in pads, gels or particles and promote the deposit of newly formed collagen in the wound bed. They can be used on any type of wound with any type of drainage. Some specific brands require the wound to be free ofÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#necrotic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">necrotic</span></a>Â tissue.</p> <p><strong>Examples:Â <br />pads â€“ Promogran Prisma, Promogran Matrix (collagen with silver), BioPad, Fibracol Plus (alginate/collagen combination)Â <br />gel â€“ Stimulen GelÂ <br />powder â€“ StimulenÂ </strong><br /><br /><strong></strong><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br />Any type of wound with minimal, moderate or heavy drainage Some specific brands require the wound to be free ofÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#necrotic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">necrotic</span></a>Â tissueÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Provides a moist healing environmentÂ <br />Some brands reduce destructive elements in wound fluid to â€œkick-startâ€ healing while allowing the patientâ€™sÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#growth"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">growth factors</span></a>Â to effectively heal the wound Promotes tissueÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#granulation"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">granulation</span></a>Â andÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#epithelialization"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">epithelialization</span></a>Â Burns GraftsÂ <br /><br /><strong></strong><strong>Contraindications</strong>Â <br />none knownÂ </p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a id="hydro" name="hydro"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">HYDROCOLLOID DRESSINGS</a></strong><br /><strong>Can be either a primary or a secondary dressingÂ </strong><br /><br />Wafer-type dressings that containÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#hydroactive"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">hydroactive</span></a>Â particles which, when in contact with woundÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>, form a fluid/gel environment over the wound bed.Â  They can be self-adheringÂ  with a surface that repells water, bacteria and other outside contaminants.Â  They are consideredÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#occlusive"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">occlusive</span></a>Â or semi-<a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#occlusive"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">occlusive</span></a>.</p> <p><strong>Examples:Â <br />Tegaderm ThinÂ <br />Reliamed border sacralÂ <br />Reliamed beveledÂ <br />Flexicol borderedÂ <br />Medihoney sheet (hydrocolloid with honey)Â <br />Medihoney tube Â </strong>Â <br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br /><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#partial_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">partial thickness</span></a>Â to shallowÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#full_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">full thickness</span></a>Â woundsÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />maintains a moist wound environment provides protection and insulation to a healing wound facilitatesÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#autolytic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">autolytic debridement</span></a>Â <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications for use</strong>Â <br />infected woundsÂ <br />wounds with heavyÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>, deep cavities, sinus tracts (unless used as a secondary dressing over packing)Â <br />BurnsÂ <br />GraftsÂ </p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="hydrofera"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/proddetail.asp?prod=foam%5Fhydrofera">HYDROFERA BLUE</a></strong>Â <br />Foam impregnated with Methylene Blue and Gentian VioletÂ <br /><br /><strong></strong><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br />Wounds containing bacteria, yeast and fungusÂ <br /><br /><strong></strong><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Provides a protective, bacteriostatic cover which may help prevent infectionÂ <br /><br />When used under anÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#occlusive">occlusive</a>Â dressing, product will create a mildÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#negative">negative pressure</a>Â that will reduce anÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#epiboly">epiboly</a>Â (rolled edge).Â <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications</strong>Â <br />None knownÂ </p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="hydrogel"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">HYDROGEL DRESSINGS</a></strong><br /><strong>Must be covered with a secondary cover dressing</strong>Â <br /><br />Vary in composition but most areÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#nonocclusive">non-occlusive</a>Â and water or glycerin based, depending on manufacturer.Â  This product comes in sheets, impregnated in gauze and in gel form.</p> <p><strong>Examples:Â <br />hydrogel sheets â€“ Spand-Gel, AvogelÂ <br />amorphous hydrogel â€“ NormlgelÂ </strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br />Any type of wound needing additional moistureÂ <br />BurnsÂ <br />GraftsÂ <br />Sheet form can be used for quicker healing of cosmetic procedures and/or scar reductionÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Adds moisture to dry woundsÂ <br />Maintains a moist wound environmentÂ <br />FacilitatesÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#autolytic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">autolytic debridement</span></a>.Â <br />Avogel sheets provide a barrier to prevent heat and water loss through the skin which aids in scar reductionÂ <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications</strong>Â <br />Because of the moist nature of these dressings, care must be taken to observe the wound edges and protect fromÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#maceration"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">maceration</span></a>.Â </p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="hydrogelanti"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">HYDROGEL</a>Â -Â <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#antimicrobial">ANTIMICROBIAL</a></strong><br /><br /><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#amorphous"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Amorphous</span></a>Â hydrogel combined withÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#sodium"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">sodium hypochlorite</span></a>Â for elimination of bacteria, multi-resistant bacteria, viruses and fungi.</p> <p><strong>Example:Â <br />Anasept</strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br />Any wound needing additional moisture and infection protectionÂ <br />Dry wounds with signs of infectionÂ <br />BurnsÂ <br />GraftsÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Provides moisture to a wound site while eliminating or preventing infectionÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#biocompatible"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Biocompatible</span></a>Â with other dressingsÂ <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications</strong>Â <br />None knownÂ </p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="hydrogelsilver"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">HYDROGEL WITH SILVER</a></strong><br /><br />Hydrogel with silver added forÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#antimicrobial"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">antimicrobial</span></a>Â benefits</p> <p><strong>Examples:Â <br />SilverSeptÂ <br />Elta silver hydrogelÂ </strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br />Wounds needing additional moisture and infection protectionÂ <br />Dry wounds with evidence of infectionÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Provides moisture in a wound site while eliminating or preventing infectionÂ <br />Absorbs a small amount of woundÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>Â <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications:</strong>Â <br />Should not be utilized in conjuction with Tegaderm Matrix as deactivation of both dressings will resultÂ </p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="tape"></a>HYPERTONIC DRESSINGS</strong><br /><br />Available in impregnated gauze and gel form, these dressings provide a high sodium chloride level to eliminateÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#necrotic">necrotic</a>Â tissue.</p> <p><strong>Examples:Â <br />Hypergel â€“ gel used to break down eschar ofÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#necrotic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">necrotic</span></a>Â tissueÂ <br />Mesaltâ€“ dry sheet or strip (used to wick infection out of tunneling areas)Â <br />CurasaltÂ <span class="tablehd">â€“Â </span>moist hypertonic tape</strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br /><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#autolytic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">autolytic debridement</span></a>Â ofÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#necrotic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">necrotic</span></a>Â tissue fills wound space to wick drainage out of a tunnel orÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#undermining"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">undermining</span></a>Â provides or encourages a moist environmentÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />createsÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#osmotic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">osmotic</span></a>Â changes in the wound environment to encourage debridementÂ <br /><br /><strong></strong><strong>Contraindications:</strong>Â <br />cannot apply toÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#granulation"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">granulation</span></a>Â tissue as it can cause a burning sensationÂ </p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="foam"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">FOAM DRESSINGS, BORDERED FOAM DRESSINGS, FOAM DRESSINGS WITH SILVER</a></strong><br /><strong>May be used as a primary or secondary dressing</strong><br /><br />Available as self-adhering or non-adherent (though some may have adhesive border). Polyurethane foam dressings which have an absorbent wound contact surface and most have a moisture-repellant outer surface which isÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#nonocclusive"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">non-occlusive</span></a>.Â  Ability to absorb<a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>Â is dependant upon thickness and density of the dressing.</p> <p><strong>Examples:Â <br />Mepilex (with Safetac technology)Â <br />Mepilex Border (water resistant with Safetac technology)Â <br />PolymemÂ <br />Polymem Dot (with silver)Â <br />Reliamed</strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br />Partial andÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#full_thkns">full thickness</a>Â woundsÂ <br />To cover wounds containing packing materialÂ <br /><br /><strong></strong><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Absorbs excessÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a>Â to preventÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#maceration"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">maceration</span></a>Â <br />Provides a moist wound environmentÂ <br />Insulation and protectionÂ <br /><br /><strong></strong><strong>Contraindications</strong>Â <br />Wounds with dry escharÂ <br />No or minimalÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudate</span></a></p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="moisture"></a>MOISTURE REGULATION</strong><br /><strong>Requires a secondary dressing to cover it</strong>Â <br /><br />An inert breathable polymer combined with a nonwoven medium which provides fluid balance at the wound surface instead of within the dressing.</p> <p><strong>Example:Â <br />TheraGauzeÂ </strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for:</strong>Â <br /><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#partial_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">partial</span></a>Â andÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#full_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">full thickness</span></a>Â wounds of any typeÂ <br />graftsÂ <br />burnsÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action:</strong>Â <br />Controls moisture and facilitates healing by releasing or absorbing moisture based on wound conditionsÂ <br />PreventsÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#maceration"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">maceration</span></a>Â <br />High oxygenÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#permeability"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">permeability</span></a>Â <br />Compatible with most other medicationsÂ <br />One-piece removalÂ <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications:</strong>Â <br />Wet wounds unlessÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#fenestrated"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">fenestrated</span></a></p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="mmpred"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#mmps">MMP</a>Â REDUCTION</strong><br /><strong>Requires a secondary dressing to cover it</strong>Â <br /><br />Cellulose impregnated with potassium, zinc, calcium and rubidium.Â </p> <p><strong>ExamplesÂ <br />Tegaderm MatrixÂ <br />EpiMax</strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for</strong>Â <br />All types of wounds including burns, grafts and incisionsÂ <br />â€œKick-startingâ€ stalled woundsÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />Corrects the MMP balance in the wound site enabling the patientâ€™sÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#growth"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">growth factors</span></a>Â to heal the woundÂ <br />Creates a moist wound environment while preventingÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#maceration"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">maceration</span></a>Â <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications</strong>Â <br />Use with silver products will cause deactivation of both products.Â </p> <hr /> <p><br /><strong><a name="transparent"></a><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/wound-care-products.asp?cat=13&amp;id=woundcare">TRANSPARENT FILM DRESSINGS</a></strong><br /><br />Semipermeable membranes which are self-adhering, thin and waterproof. They allow gaseous exchange between the wound bed and the environment, but water, bacteria or other contaminants cannot penetrate the dressing</p> <p><strong>Examples:Â <br />MeporeÂ <br />ReliaMed Transparent Thin film dressings</strong><br /><br /><strong>Indicated for:</strong>Â <br /><a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#partial_thkns"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">partial thickness</span></a>Â woundsÂ <br />stage II ulcersÂ <br />dry,Â <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#necrotic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">necrotic</span></a>Â wounds requiring debridementÂ <br /><br /><strong>Action</strong>Â <br />helps to maintain a moist wound surfaceÂ <br />facilitatesÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#autolytic"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">autolytic debridement</span></a>.Â Â <br /><br /><strong>Contraindications for use:</strong>Â <br />heavyÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#exudate"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">exudating</span>Â </a>woundsÂ <br />deep cavities, sinus tracts orÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#undermining"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">undermining</span></a>Â (unless used as a secondary dressing) or wounds withÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#friable"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">friable</span></a>Â skin in theÂ <a href="http://www.admedonline.com/education.asp#periwound"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">periwound</span></a>Â area.</p>', 'Product Terminology', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'product-terminology', '', '', '2013-04-10 17:10:03', '2013-04-10 17:10:03', '', 0, 'http://admedonlinenew.dev:8888/?p=11', 6, 'post', '', 0),
